# 13. Si tu as le vrai domain, Donc tu doit utiliser le Let’s Encrypt

Si tu as un domain

```text
broapp.domainkamu.com
```

Créer DNS A record:

```text
broapp.domainkamu.com -> INGRESS_IP
```

Puis créer le ClusterIssuer:

```bash
EMAIL=you@example.com
```

```bash
cat > letsencrypt-clusterissuer.yaml <<EOF
apiVersion: cert-manager.io/v1
kind: ClusterIssuer
metadata:
  name: letsencrypt-http01
spec:
  acme:
    email: ${EMAIL}
    server: https://acme-v02.api.letsencrypt.org/directory
    privateKeySecretRef:
      name: letsencrypt-http01-account-key
    solvers:
      - http01:
          ingress:
            ingressClassName: nginx
EOF
```

Apply:

```bash
kubectl apply -f letsencrypt-clusterissuer.yaml
```

Puis le value de la production:

```bash
REAL_HOST=broapp.domainkamu.com
```

```bash
cat > values-prod-letsencrypt.yaml <<EOF
service:
  type: ClusterIP
  port: 80

ingress:
  enabled: true
  className: nginx
  annotations:
    cert-manager.io/cluster-issuer: letsencrypt-http01
    nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/ssl-redirect: "true"
  hosts:
    - host: ${REAL_HOST}
      paths:
        - path: /
          pathType: Prefix
  tls:
    - secretName: broapp-letsencrypt-tls
      hosts:
        - ${REAL_HOST}
EOF
```

Upgrade:

```bash
helm upgrade $APP_RELEASE ./broapp \
  -n $APP_NS \
  -f values-prod-letsencrypt.yaml \
  --atomic \
  --wait \
  --timeout 10m
```

Check:

```bash
kubectl get certificate -n $APP_NS
kubectl get challenge,order -n $APP_NS
```

